    "A New and Concise Bible Dictionary": "Land or district in the southern part of Palestine. Joshua 10: 41; Joshua 11:\n2. Son of Ashur and Naarah, of the tribe of Judah. 1 Chr. 4: 6.\n2. Son of Mushi, a son of Merari. 1 Chr. 23:\n2. Jerijah. [Jeri'jah] See JERIAH. Jerimoth. [Jeri'moth] 1,\n2. Son of Bela and son of Becher, Benjamites. 1 Chr. 7: 7, 8.\n2. The lords of the Philistines however objected, and Achish begged David `[char_David_Rut_4]` to return. See DAVID.\n2. Another king of Gath, to whom the servants of Shimei fled, which led to Shimei's death.1 Kings 2: 39,\n2. The LXX do not treat it as a proper name: the passage there reads &quot;And there was found in the city (\u03c0 \u1f79 \u03bb\u03b5\u03b9), in the palace, a volume.&quot; The Vulgate has &quot;Et inventum est in Ecbatanis.&quot; Apparently history alludes to two cities named Ecbatana: one associated with the ruins at Takht-i-Suleiman, 36 28' N, 47 18' E; the other identified with the modern Hamadan, 34 48' N, 48 26' E, anciently the summer residence of Persian kings, and where the records of the kingdom were apparently kept. This is most probably the Achmetha of scripture. Travellers state that the Jews exhibit a tomb in their charge in the midst of the city, which is the reputed tomb of Mordecai and Esther `[char_Esther_Ref]`. Achor, [A'chor] Valley of. Achor signifies 'trouble,' and was the place where Achan was stoned for having troubled Israel by taking the accursed thing. Joshua 7:\n2. City in the lot of Asher, but from which the inhabitants were not driven out. Joshua 19: 29; Judges 1:\n2. One of the wives of Esau, daughter of Elon the Hittite and thus 'a daughter of Canaan:' she bare to Esau his first-born son Eliphaz, who became the father of seven of the dukes of Edom. Gen. 36: 2, 4, 15,\n2. Son of Ethan, a Gershonite. 1 Chr. 4: 41.\n2. A priest of the family of Harim. Neh. 12:\n2. Son or daughter of one in the tribe of Judah. 1 Chr. 4:\n2. One who stood by Ezra when he read the law. Neh. 8: 4.\n2. Son of Mibsam, a descendant of Simeon. 1 Chr. 4: 25,\n2. Misrephothmaim. [Mis'rephoth-maim] City in connection with Zidon. Joshua 11: 8; Joshua 13:\n2. Son of Terah and brother of Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`. Gen. 11: 26-29; Gen. 22: 20, 23; Gen. 24: 10-47; Gen. 29: 5; Gen. 31:\n2. Nahshon. [Nah'shon] Son of Amminadab, and a prince of Judah. Num. 1: 7; Num. 2: 3; Num. 7: 12, 17; Num. 10: 14; Ruth 4: 20; 1 Chr. 2: 10,\n2. David `[char_David_Rut_4]`'s wife a woman of Jezreel: she accompanied David `[char_David_Rut_4]` in his flight from Saul; and, while residing at Ziklag, was taken captive when the city was burned by the Amalekites; but was recovered. 1 Sam. 25: 43; 1 Sam. 27: 3; 1 Sam. 30: 5,\n2. Son of Dishan, a son of Seir. Gen. 36: 28; 1 Chr. 1: 42.\n2. Son of Shimhi, a Benjamite. 1 Chr. 8: 19. 3. 'The Shiphmite,' overseer of David `[char_David_Rut_4]`'s wine stores. 1 Chr. 27: 27.",
    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "who is a vegetarian. Those kind of people reason that since your body is the temple of the Holy Spirit that you defile that temple when you eat something that is bad for you, like red meat. So they try to convince you that if you want to be right with God you have to eat like they eat. I have seen several young men like that come through the school here. Inevitably they become obsessed with health food, diets, etc., and they drop out of the ministry altogether. Now, here are the rules on food:\n2. If you can bow your head over it and thank God for it with a clear conscience, then eat it; if you can\u2019t, then don\u2019t.\n2. Would I like to have the Lord find me doing it when He returns?\nverse 2: \u201cLet every one of us please his neighbour for his good to edification.\u201d Now,\nverse 2 presents a problem: it is one of those famous \u201ccontradictions\u201d in the Bible.\nVerse 2 comes into conflict with what [v_Gal_1_10] Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` said in Galatians 1:10. \u201cFor do I now persuade men, or God? or do I seek to please men? For if I yet pleased men, I should not be the servant of Christ.\u201d So how do we please men when we are told not to, and how do we please our neighbor when are told to? The answer is in the context of each passage. In Galatians 1 Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` is talking about preaching the Gospel to unsaved people. The content of preaching is not to please men; it is to please God. [v_Rom_15_2] Romans 15:2 is addressing our conduct in regards to other Christians. You can compromise your practice on a questionable thing in order to get along with the brethren without compromising your convictions. You can change your diet to accommodate a weaker brother without changing one thing you can believe from the word of God. You can curb your Sunday activity to be a good testimony to those around you without observing Sunday as the Sabbath. Just because you have the liberty to drink water out of a Seagram\u2019s Seven bottle doesn\u2019t mean you should do it.",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "Ver. 2. [That these] made war with Bera `[char_Bera_Gen_14]` king of Sodom, etc.] A city in the plain of Jordan, which with the four following made the Pentapolis, or five cities of the plain. Strabo f956 says, in this place formerly were thirteen cities, the metropolis of which was Sodom, and which yet had remaining a compass of sixty furlongs; according to Dr. Lightfoot f957, it should be placed in the southern extremity of the lake Asphaltites, whereas it is usually set in the maps in the northern bounds of it: and with Birsha `[char_Birsha_Gen_14]` king of Gomorrah; another city in the plain of Jordan, called by Solinus f958 Gomorrum: Shinab `[char_Shinab_Gen_14]` king of Admah; a third city situated in the same plain: and Shemeber `[char_Shemeber_Gen_14]` king of Zeboiim; a fourth city of the plain, which seems to have its name from the pleasantness of its situation: and the king of Bela, which is Zoar; so it was afterwards called by Lot, [v_Gen_19_20] being a little city, (<011920>Genesis 19:20,22); but before, Bela; the name of its king is not mentioned, being a person of no great note and importance, and his city small.\nVer."
